Plots of distributions of answers by country

Mainly to inspect the distribution of nonnormal values (-5, -2, -1) Especially, -2: No answer and -1:Dont know are pretty prevalent in some countries.

This is the density plot for the V152 tax the rich, Colombia has ALL of answers as -4 Not asked. Thus it has been dropped as well. After deleting Colombia, Georgia has 14.4& of nonnormal values

For the purpose of exploratory analysis, I deleted entries with at least one answer being unnormal (<0), in those troublemaking countries: Georgia, Japan, Bulgaria, Serbia, Slovenia. The percentage of the normal entries that are left are such percentage:

## original size 
d = c()
for (cn in c("Georgia", "Japan", "Bulgaria", "Serbia", "Slovenia")){
  a = data_wv5_6up %>%
    filter(country == cn) %>%
    nrow()
  d = c(d, a)
}

print(paste("The originial size for", c("Georgia", "Japan", "Bulgaria", "Serbia", "Slovenia"), "are:", d))
## [1] "The originial size for Georgia are: 1500" 
## [2] "The originial size for Japan are: 1096"   
## [3] "The originial size for Bulgaria are: 1001"
## [4] "The originial size for Serbia are: 1220"  
## [5] "The originial size for Slovenia are: 1037"
## filtered size
b = c()
for (cn in c("Georgia", "Japan", "Bulgaria", "Serbia", "Slovenia")){
  a = data_wv5_6up %>%
    filter(country == cn) %>%
    filter(V152>0 & V153>0 & V154>0 & V155 >0 & V156 >0 & V157 >0 & V161>0) %>%
    nrow()
  b = c(b,a)
}

print(paste("After DELETION of nonnormal entries, the size for", c("Georgia", "Japan", "Bulgaria", "Serbia", "Slovenia"), "are:", b))
## [1] "After DELETION of nonnormal entries, the size for Georgia are: 1004"
## [2] "After DELETION of nonnormal entries, the size for Japan are: 718"   
## [3] "After DELETION of nonnormal entries, the size for Bulgaria are: 693"
## [4] "After DELETION of nonnormal entries, the size for Serbia are: 958"  
## [5] "After DELETION of nonnormal entries, the size for Slovenia are: 806"
### The percentage of the normal entries for countries: "Georgia", "Japan", "Bulgaria", "Serbia", "Slovenia"

print(paste("The percentage of the normal entries that are left for", c("Georgia", "Japan", "Bulgaria", "Serbia", "Slovenia"), "are:", b/d))
## [1] "The percentage of the normal entries that are left for Georgia are: 0.669333333333333" 
## [2] "The percentage of the normal entries that are left for Japan are: 0.655109489051095"   
## [3] "The percentage of the normal entries that are left for Bulgaria are: 0.692307692307692"
## [4] "The percentage of the normal entries that are left for Serbia are: 0.785245901639344"  
## [5] "The percentage of the normal entries that are left for Slovenia are: 0.777242044358727"

The troublemakers are mainly Japan, Bulgaria, Serbia, Georgia Slovenia etc which are mostly eastern Europe or Asia countries. They usually have above 10% of nonnormal values in at least one of the items.

The main issue we need to deal with are those -2 and -1s. Because there are many entries that are populated with not only one negaties, I think we might want to delete them at all.
